STATE OF NEBRASKA OFFICE OF THE AUDITOR OF PUBLIC ACCOUN fS Lincoln, Nebraska, December 1, 1910 To His Excellency, Aahton C. Shallenberger, Governor of the State of Nebraska. Dear Sir: — Complying with the this department, we take pleasure in report. The tabular statements were itatutes relative to the reports of ubmitting to you our first biennial compiled from the records of this office and a study of the record, as made, will give you a technical, de - tailed and exact financial statement of the condition of the several de - partments under our state government. At the close of the last biennium, November 30, 1908, the interest bearing debt of the state amounted to $836,417.28, consisting of registered warrants on the General Fund of $71 - Temporary University Fund warrants. $117,846.90. At the close of business November 30, 1910, the interest bearing debt of the state was $182,334.61. all of which was Temporary University Fund. The last of the General Fund warrants waa taken up January 29, 1910, and there is now in the General Fund $154,920.06 and in the Redemption Fund $1,124.86, showing an improve - ment over two years ago of $874,487.71. In the registered Univ. Fund warrants there is an increase of $64,487.71; these warrants are a part of the state's investment. Statement Number Four shows the total estimated income of the General Fund for the fiscal period commencing April 1, 1911, and ending March 31, 1913, to be $4,675,502.21. Against this estimated amount of in - come in the General Fund is placed the estimated expenditures to main - tain our state department, amounting to $4,503,890.00, leaving a balance on the right side of the ledger of $171,612.21. It should be gratifying to the citizens of Nebraska to note the splendid financial condition of our state and most especially to point with pride to Statement Number Twenty-one, which shows investments for the Permanent School Fund $8,097,355.41 Permanent University Fund 207,509.37 Agricultural College Endowment Fund 482,825.24 Normal Endowment Fund 76,000.00 A grand total of invested school funds of ..." $8,863,690.02 The interest for the last biennial period amounted to $569,760.95. 1 Through the State Accountant I have audited the accounts of the I normal schools, the state institutions and the State University. Bnd that great improvement coald be secured by having these several

6 institutions adept a uniform system of accounting and having a report sent to this office once each month. This report would give a complete check on the institution and, for comparative work, would be of much value. The accountant, as per the statute, attended the meetings of the Board of Purchase and Supplies. In our audit of the State University the work was so comprehensive that we hand you this examination sepa:ate from the report. We found the condition of this institution most excellent, that the purchasing de - partment had exercised great care in securing competition on the supplies purchased and that the moneys furnished by the state had been judiciously expended. A careful review of this report in detail will show the receipts and disbursements. In auditing this institution we find, connected with the University, three affiliated schools — Medicine, Dentistry and Music. The affiliation between the University and the Dental Collet contractual relation. The college collects the fee for the entire course, then pays the fees into the University for the student to get the specific studies to enable him to complete the course. We do not find this is done to the exclusion of all other colleges. The School of Medicine is indeed so closely connected with the University that it might, with propriety, be said to be a University School of Medicine, eliminating the word "affiliated". The regents control the school; the University is represented at the trustees meeting of the Medical College and a complete statement of the accounts is furnished each year. This college has developed by evolution and we do not be - lieve that the Chancellor, the Regents or the Trustees of the Medical College would raise objections to having all fees received from this in - stitution paid directly to the state and all disbursements audited by the Regents, thereby eliminating the word "affiliated" and making it in truth a University School of Medicine. The affiliated School of Music is a private enterprise, run for revenue, and using the name of the State University as a trade mark. Its articles of incorporation as a private corporation are on file in the office of the Secretary of State. The institutional head hires the teachers, prescribes courses of study and reaps the profit without the authority or interference of the Board of Regents of the State University. I find, on looking at their catalogue, they put on the outside cover "The University School of Music, Lincoln, Nebraska;" on another page, "affiliated with the University of Nebraska;" in fact the catalogue is replete with advertising of the University. In the calendar issued by the University we find the School of Music mentioned as affiliated and after careful inquiry we have no hesitancy in stating that the name of the State University of Nebraska should not be used to foster and build an absolutely private enterprise; that the word "affiliation" in this case is a misnomer; that the revenues of said institution in no way find their way into the state funds; that neither the Chancellor nor any of the Regents have a part in the administration and that, in our judgment, the

REPORT OF AUDITOR OF PUBLIC ACCOUNTS sole meaning of the word "affiiliate" is to permit this private enterprise to trade on that which is valuable— the name of the State University. And I recommend the specific prohibition of the further use of the term "affiliated with the State University" and believe that in taking this step the rich state of Nebraska can well afford to establish its own de - partment of music at the State University, cut in two the expense at tuition and make the department self-sustaining. During the biennium just closed the business of the bond department of this office has far exceeded the business of any like period in the history of the state; it having examined, approved and registered 347 separate issues of bonds of the different counties, precincts, drainage districts, cities, villages and school districts, amounting in the aggregate to $4,871,071.00, besides handling almost 11,000,000.00 worth of depository bank bonds, filed by 130 different banks of the state. In addition to this a large number of bond issues have been re. on account of failure in complying erning their issuance. with the provisions of the laws gov- I would recommend that a sta the legislature making it the duty office, at least once each year, the by the different drainage districts so that a check can be kept on the :ute be enacted at the next session of of each county clerk to report to this amount of bonds paid off or refunded cities, villages and school district* amounts of each outs:anding. I our present law no bends are reported on when paid, excepting those of counties and precincts, and as a result, there is no way of determining the amounts outstanding of any of the others. I also recommend that the statute under which lighting bonds ef villages are voted be re-enacted and all bonds heretofore issued under the provisions of the same be legalized, for the reason that the title of the bill providing for this class of bonds did not include villages. The County Treasurer Examiners for this department have kept their audit well within the law, which requires these examinations to be made within two year periods. We expect, during the next two year bring these examinations down to yearly periods. With two more ex - aminers we could check the offices of County Judge, Clerk of Court. County Superintendent, County Clerk and County Sheriff, and, as many counties are now, at their own expense, having this audit made, it appeals to us that it would be in accordance with good business to make a com - plete audit of all county offices, as these examinations protect the officer as well as the public. These examiners are busily employed throughout the year; their work calls for a degree of proficiency equal to a bank examiner and I must respectfully ask that the salary be made equal to that of our bank examiners — $1,800.00 per annum. Statement Number Eight B shows a summary of the delinquent taxes due from counties by years from 1859 to the present time. Comparing this table with the statement made two years ago shows no appreciable decrease; in fact, the greatest portion of this tax will never be collected

REPORT OF AUDITOR OF PUBLIC ACCOI 8 and while this item on tbe books of this office shows an indebtedness of the counties and an asset of the state it is a false asset. An Investigation of the accounts of some of the counties shows that If the proper credits were given that most of this delinquency and, in some instances all of it, would be wiped out. These credits, consist of uncollectible personal tax, refunds on account of erroneous taxation, errors found in the footings of the tax list after same has been reported to this office, and by the operation of the scavenger law ; the first and last items being most important. Tbe present law allows the counties credit for uncollectible personal tax after three years. A few counties have made returns on some of the years, but most of the counties make no returne. The law makes no provision of credit from a county where, under the scavenger law, the selling price is less than the face of the tax list. This difference in some counties would amount to many thousands of dollars, yet, knowing this condition, it becomes necessary year after year to report these "assets" of the state and to continue to spread upon the tax ledger the small items reported, making an indefinite, continuing account showing erroneous conclusions. I trust that you will deem this matter of sufficient importance to refer to a legislative committee for consideration. Auditors preceding me have called attention to the fact that some of the special appropriations are placed in absolute control of one man and that the bills do not have to be allowed by a State Board or Regents. This is contrary to our entire system and while the appropriations may have all been expended honestly it is bad practice to continue so un - businesslike a policy, and action should be taken to have these ex - penditures made under the supervision of some State Board. »Most particularly do I desire to call your attention to the department insurance. Every citizen of this state is directly interested in this department of the state. During the last biennial period this department produced revenue for the state in an amount of $75,910.86 of fees and $168,810.74 of taxes; a total of $244,721.60. The entire amount appropriated by the last legisla - ture for the maintenance of this department, salaries, office expenses, etc., was only $11,680.00. It is practically impossible to give the state the proper service with this meagre, inadequate appropriation and, be - lieving that it is the desire of the people to establish and maintain a strong working department, we have asked for the necessary appropria - tion to carry on this work. The citizens of Nebraska, during 1908 and 1909, paid out for in - surance $24,474,635.00. This amount covers premiums paid for all classes of this industry. The companies paid back to the people in losses in - curred $10,836,883.00. This statement of fact readily proves that one of the great business interests of Nebraska is insurance. My department has made a careful, unprejudiced study of the con - ditions.such as the contracts issued, the methods used by companies and

9 discrimination between the assured, and, with the object in view of pro - tecting our insuring public and for the purpose of fostering this industry we expect to submit remedial legislation at the coming session of our ;tture and we (In the interests of the people of this state) earnestly ask your co-operation. We believe in fostering these institutions in our state and they do have our co-operation and support, as proven by the receipts of premiums but we do not believe that they should, any more than any other industry, prosper by fraud and wrong doing and it is your duty, the duty of my department and the duty of the legislature, by statute, to make illegal and criminal, all fraud, misrepresentation, licentious and high pressure business transacted in this commonwealth. Much scandal, nationally, has been created in the past few years in the promotion of companies. We have in existence professional pi - ers who organize companies for the sole purpose of exacting a high mission for their services, leaving the new company almost hopeless. This species of business is fraud, pure and simple, perpetrated in the daylight Not one line of law is on the statute prescribing the methods to be employed or fixing the amount that can be lawfully taken for ex - penses and promotion. We shall ask for plain law governing this con - dition. tin our judgment, the position of Insurance Commissioner should b€ e elective, placing him directly at the disposition of the people. This ness being a profession or science, a Commissioner, if he is pro - sive and honest, becomes more valuable to the state each year. His i of office should be for six years and his salary sufficient to com - d the best talent. While it would require a constitutional amend - t to attain this result, we firmly believe that taking into consideration great financial interests of our state and the solidity of this depart - t that this matter is of great importance, and the Commissioner ild be directly subject to the people he serves. tOur insurance laws are the patchwork of years. When a company red to organize in the past they had law adopted for this specific pur - :. The results are an indefinite, cumbersome code. In this coming session of the legislature, we expect to have intro - duced, as department measures only, a few bills touching the moat important points to be remedied, but in the interest of our state; and as our legislative period does not give the proper time for the grave consideration these laws deserve, we think it would be advisable to have a committee appointed for the purpose of codifying the insurance laws. R to report to the next legislature. We most respectfully submit this report, sincerely asking your Ex - cellency to give our recommendations more than ordinary consideration. Our ideas were gleaned from the book of experience and the spirit that prompted the statements was the welfare of the state of which we are so justly proud. Respectfully, SILAS R. BARTON, Auditor of Public Accounts
